-- Crude Options Volatility Falls as Oil Futures Little Changed
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-06-10T18:39:55Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-06-10/crude-options-volatility-falls-as-oil-futures-little-changed.html
Crude oil options volatility
declined as the underlying futures were little changed.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
August, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 20.13 percent on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange  at 2:15 p.m., versus 20.87 percent June 7.  West Texas Intermediate crude for August delivery fell 28
cents to $95.99 a barrel at 2:18 p.m. on the Nymex, the first
decline in four days. July futures declined 29 cents to $95.74.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
August $88 puts, which fell 9 cents to 44 cents a barrel on
2,538 lots at 2:18 p.m. on the Nymex. July $89 puts were the
second-most active, dropping 4 cents to 4 cents on volume of
2,467 contracts.  Puts accounted for 55 percent of electronic trading volume
today. In the prior session, puts accounted for 60 percent of
129,779 contracts.  July $90 puts were the most-active options traded June 7,
with 9,457 contracts changing hands. They fell 13 cents to 11
cents a barrel. July $100 calls rose 3 cents to 12 cents on
volume of 5,165 lots.  Open interest was highest for September $85 puts with
41,906 contracts. Next were December $105 calls with 38,914 lots
and July $110 calls with 36,914.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
